@node INTRO "LotsaBlankers.guide/Introduction"
@next REQUIREMENTS
@prev MAIN

                               @{b}@{u}INTRODUCTION@{uu}@{ub}

LotsaBlankers is a collection of excellent blankers for the @{"GarshneBlanker" link GARSHNE}
system, and a replacement Garshnelib.library with a little better AGA
support. There are many blankers out there, it's true.. But there is
always room for good blankers. This archive features a set of five
blankers, LotsaSnow, LotsaStars, LotsaPlasma, LotsaLego and
LotsaDistortion. As the smarter ones already have noticed, all of the names
begin with 'Lotsa.' (For those less familiar with english, that's some kind
of slang for 'Lots of.') It is meant to give the blankers some kind of
unity, and to imply that the blankers can do much of what they are meant to
do. For example LotsaSnow can smoothly animate over 20000 `snowflakes' on a
040/40MHz...

But what do they all do then? Here:

@{b}Garshnelib.library@{ub}

This is a replacement for Garshnelib.library, with a little better AGA
support - namely that the function copying the frontmost screen supports
AGA now.

@{b}LotsaSnow@{ub}

A blanker inspired by another blanker for GarshneBlanker named Snow, Snow
is nice, but Dag figured why not make one that can really put snowflakes on
the screen, so he made LotsaSnow. The idea is quite simple, it draws
snowflakes (white pixels) that slowly fall down your screen, excellent for
those nastily hot summer-days.

@{b}LotsaPlasma@{ub}

This one is a plasma-blanker, but it's a little special. It generates a
double-plasma on the screen, that is then animated with two dimensional
colorcycling. Got that? No? Well, install them and check it out!

@{b}LotsaStars@{ub}

You might think that this one is a normal Stars-blanker, that simply draws
lots of stars on the screen, but it's not. This one uses a special
color-cycling method to get many colorful stars on screen, followed by
colorful trails. As with LotsaPlasma, you have to try it out to see what
it's like. Does not work on over 8-bitplane screens.

@{b}LotsaLego@{ub}

For all of you who miss the times playing with Lego(ą) from when you were
younger, and for all of you who still do play with Lego. This little
blanker builds random constructions of Lego on the screen, over and over
again...

@{b}LotsaDistortion@{ub}

Now this is the real pearl of this package. It is inspired by the 'Lens'
blanker by Nick Christie also available for GarshneBlanker. Lens was cool,
entertained us for some time, but it didn't quite cooperate with our
systems and was a @{i}tad @{ui}slow. Also, at a CircleSoft meeting some time ago,
Rofa (a Circle member) introduced us to the corresponding blanker under
Windows 95, it had things like Twirl and Black Hole along with the
normal Lens. Facing these things, LotsaDistortion had to be born.

The idea is that it renders a distortion, and then moves this around on the
screen. An example would be a lens, that you move around on the screen, but
LotsaDistorton features much more than just a lens, other distortions are
Ripples, Bump, Black Hole, Twirl, something we call Exponential, and our
favourite; Flower. (There is an additional sneak-surprise too... :-)

LotsaDistortion eats quite a bit of CPU-power, so you might want to have
some better number-cruncher than your 68000 or 68020. A 68040/40MHz does
quite fine.

And as far as we know, it is the fastest and most configurable of its kind.
Rejoice!

So there, now try them! And @{"contact us" link CONTACT} if you have problems!

--

@{b}ą@{ub} Lego is a registered trademark of Lego corporation something.
  Legos are small tiles, created in a very intellectual way, so that you
  can build very complex constructions of it. For more info, travel to
  LegoLand in Denmark.

@endnode
@node BUGS "LotsaBlankers.guide/Known problems"

                              @{b}@{u}KNOWN PROBLEMS@{uu}@{ub}

    @{b}o@{ub} It is very possible that some of the blankers (esp. LotsaStars and
      LotsaDistortion.) don't work with graphics cards. If you are willing
      to code a version that functions on graphics cards, @{"contact us" link CONTACT} and
      we may be able to work something out.

    @{b}o@{ub} LotsaStars does not exit when precalculating, so you might have to
      wait a few seconds if you happen to try to unblank when it is
      precalculating.

    @{b}o@{ub} When the double-buffering in LotsaDistortion is turned on, sometimes
      a short line is left flickering on the bottom of the screen, it is
      harmless, though.

If you have problems, @{"contact us" link CONTACT} for technical support.

@endnode
@node FUTURE "LotsaBlankers.guide/Future"

                                  @{b}@{u}FUTURE@{uu}@{ub}

We may be releasing another replacement for the Garshnelib.library, with
better AGA support, and some extra features in the preferences. It depends
on the response we get from our users.

As for blankers, we have some partially finished ones that we may release
in the future as 'EvenMoreBlankers', or something similar.

All of the future depends mostly on user-response however, so if you have
anything you would like to say to us, do it!

Please read the @{"contacts page" link CONTACT} to find out how to contact us.

@endnode
@node REQUIREMENTS "LotsaBlankers.guide/Requirements"
@next INSTALLATION
@prev INTRO

                               @{b}@{u}REQUIREMENTS@{uu}@{ub}

LotsaSnow, LotsaStars, and LotsaLego run happily on any system
equipped with the following:

    @{b}o@{ub} @{"Garshneblanker" link GARSHNE} v3.6 (rev 38.8) or higher.
    @{b}o@{ub} AmigaOS v3.0 or higher.
    @{b}o@{ub} A 020 or better processor.
    @{b}o@{ub} The AGA chipset, or 100% compatible.

Garshneblanker requires MUI or BGUI, they are GUI systems for AmigaOS, you
can find them both on Aminet.

Many functions of the blankers are hard-coded for planar graphics,
especially LotsaSnow, therefore they may well fail on systems using
Graphics-cards.

LotsaStars won't work on screens with a depth over 8 bitplanes
(256 colors).

@endnode
@node INSTALLATION "LotsaBlankers.guide/Installation"
@next USAGE
@prev REQUIREMENTS

                               @{b}@{u}INSTALLATION@{uu}@{ub}

Before you install, be sure that you have @{"Garshneblanker" link GARSHNE} installed.

The simplest way to install LotsaBlankers is to start the
installer-script, simply double click on the icon from the Workbench.

If this would fail, however, you should copy all the files from the
'Blankers' directory to the directory where your blankers are installed,
and the documentation where you like.
@endnode
@node USAGE "LotsaBlankers.guide/Usage"
@next HINTS
@prev INSTALLATION

                                 @{b}@{u}SETTINGS@{uu}@{ub}

After you have installed the blankers, you must set them up. This is done
in the usual @{"GarshneBlanker" link GARSHNE} way, from GarshneBlanker prefs. Each blanker's
options are explained in their own chapter, but the best way to find things
out is to play around with the settings, and consult the manual for
adjustments you find confusing.

                             @{"   LotsaSnow     " link SET_SNOW}
                             @{"   LotsaStars    " link SET_STARS}
                             @{"   LotsaPlasma   " link SET_PLASMA}
                             @{"   LotsaLego     " link SET_LEGO}
                             @{" LotsaDistortion " link SET_DISTORT}

@endnode
@node HINTS "LotsaBlankers.guide/Hints and Tips"
@next CONTACT
@prev USAGE

                              @{b}@{u}HINTS AND TIPS@{uu}@{ub}

    @{b}o@{ub} Try finding the secret mode!

    @{b}o@{ub} Try finding the secret node, in this documentation!
      (Don't cheat!)

    @{b}o@{ub} Setting any of the ripple-wave amounts to 1 gives quite nice
      distortions.

    @{b}o@{ub} Try setting a real high refraction-index on Glass ripples.

    @{b}o@{ub} A low Flower Power and some two Flower leaves gives an
      amusing flower.

@endnode
@node SET_LEGO "LotsaBlankers.guide/Settings/LotsaLego"

                           @{b}@{u}SETTINGS - LOTSALEGO@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Speed@{ub}

    Sets the speed at which the Lego "construction" will be built.

@{i}NOTE: @{ui}There is one feature that comes along the GarshneBlanker package that
can be utilized very well with LotsaLego, namely Displaymode. Setting the
resolution very low will create Duplo constructions instead of usual Lego
constructions.
@endnode
@node SET_PLASMA "LotsaBlankers.guide/Settings/LotsaPlasma"

                          @{b}@{u}SETTINGS - LOTSAPLASMA@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Timeout@{ub}

    Sets the time to display current plasma before rendering new one.

@{b}Colorcycling delay@{ub}

    Sets the delay of the color-cycling. A lower value gives a higher
    cycling speed.

@{b}Dithering@{ub}

    If set to `Yes', the plasma will be dithered with random dithering.
    This option should be enabled.

@{b}Color 1@{ub}

    If set to `RGB', the color of the first plasma(ą) is set by the sliders
    below. If set to `Random', a random color-value will be used.

@{b}Color 2@{ub}

    If set to `RGB', the color of the second plasma(ą) is set by the
    sliders below. If set to `Random', a random color-value will be used.

@{b}R, G, and B@{ub} (For Color 1 and Color 2)

    Sets the RGB values for the colors. Note that the gadget above the
    respective sliders must be set to `RGB' for the adjustments to take
    effect.

--

@{b}(ą)@{ub} LotsaPlasma generates one double-plasma, i.e. two plasmas mixed
    together.

@endnode
@node SET_STARS "LotsaBlankers.guide/Settings/LotsaStars"

                           @{b}@{u}SETTINGS - LOTSASTARS@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Number of Stars@{ub}

    Sets the maximum number of stars, unless the gadget below is set to
    `Unlimited.'

    Note that the amount of stars increases with time, you will start out
    with a very small number, that will increase until this limit is
    reached.

@{b}Precalc@{ub}

    If set, LotsaStars will render the stars before blanking, so that you
    will not start out with one star and increase the amount with time.

    The `Unlimited' option is automatically turned off is Precalc is set.

@{b}Unlimited@{ub}

    If set, the number of stars will increase forever, causing panic and
    havoc all over the screen. (You will have to wait some time though.)

@{b}Number of colors@{ub}

    Amount of different star-colors. If set to 0, the stars will be
    greyscale instead of colored, and then these adjustments won't have
    any effect: `Hue offset', `Random', `White stars'...

@{b}Hue offset@{ub}

    When LotsaStars chooses the colors of the stars, it picks the colors at
    even distances along the hue scale(ą). So if you pick two colors, you
    will have one color from the beginning of the Hue-scale (red) and one
    color from the middle of the hue scale (cyan) for the stars.

    With this slider you can adjust the amount of steps along the hue-scale
    LotsaDistortion should choose the first color from. Setting this to a
    value of 60, will move all colors 60 degrees along the hue scale, which
    will make the first color yellow and the second color blue. The 'Random'
    option frees you from the trouble of adjusting this, it will pick a
    random Hue offset on each blanking.

    @{i}@{u}(ą) The hue scale@{uu}@{ui}
        The hue scale is part of the Hue-Saturation-Value (HSV or HSB)
        color-model, Hue alters the actual color, while saturation and
        value alters the brightness of it.

        The Hue scale ranges from 0 to 359 degrees. The easiest way to
        explain this is by using the colorwheel-model (as the one found in
        Palette-prefs of OS 3.x), a value of 0 is straight up on the
        colorwheel, which is red. A value of 90 degrees is to the right,
        which is between yellow and green. As it goes around in a circle,
        359 degrees is back to red. The rough scale is shown below.

                                HUE   @{FG shine}|@{FG text}  COLOR
                            @{FG shine}----------+-----------@{FG text}
                                 0    @{FG shine}|@{FG text}   Red
                                 60   @{FG shine}|@{FG text}  Yellow
                                120   @{FG shine}|@{FG text}  Green
                                180   @{FG shine}|@{FG text}   Cyan
                                240   @{FG shine}|@{FG text}   Blue
                                300   @{FG shine}|@{FG text}  Magenta
                              359/360 @{FG shine}|@{FG text}   Red

@{b}Random@{ub}

    Sets the Hue offset to a random value on each blanking.

@{b}White stars@{ub}

    If set to `Yes', the stars are colored white, while the trails are
    colorful as usual.

@endnode
@node SET_DISTORT "LotsaBlankers.guide/Settings/LotsaDistortion"

                        @{b}@{u}SETTINGS - LOTSADISTORTION@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Screen@{ub}

    Chooses the screen to clone for distortion.

@{b}Fade %@{ub}

    Sets (in percentages) how much darker the cloned screen should be than
    the original screen.

@{b}Size@{ub}

    Sets the width of the distortion, as a multiple of 32. The height is
    then adjusted according to the screen aspect to make the distortion a
    square, or circle.

@{b}Speed@{ub}

    Sets the speed at which the distortion moves across the screen. A
    higher speed makes the distortion jump over more pixels each step.
    Higher values mean more calculations, so they actually slow down the
    effect a bit. Also, a lower speed often looks better. On higher
    resolutions higher speeds look better.

@{b}Timeout@{ub}

    Sets the time to display each effect before rendering a new one.
    A value of 0 makes the first effect permanent.

@{b}System readpixel@{ub}

    If set, LotsaDistortion will use the OS's ReadPixel().
    This is slower than the built-in faster ReadPixel, and should only be
    used if the built-in one causes problems.

@{b}WaitTOF@{ub}

    If set, LotsaDistortion synchronizes the drawing of the effect with the
    refresh rate of the screen. This normally reduces flicker, but also
    slows down action a little bit. You can experiment with both modes, but
    normally you would have it turned on.

@{b}Double buffer@{ub}

    If set, LotsaDistortion will first render the effect on a hidden
    bitmap, and then copy it to the visible screen. This ultimately reduces
    flicker, but also speed.

    There are two different modes, `Evil' and `Nice'. As the name indicates
    `Nice' is a system-friendly, but slow, double buffering method, this
    mode is the last resort, if all other modes cause flickering.

    The `Evil' mode is not system-friendly, but it is much faster, it is
    practically as fast as without double buffering. It directly hacks
    the memory, so it may very well be incompatible with graphicscards.

    The `Evil' mode does not work with interlaced screens.

@{b}Glass Sphere, Bump, Twirl, Ripples, Twirples, Glass Ripples, Black Hole,
Exponential, and Flower@{ub}

    These turn the different effects on and off, if more than one effect
    is selected, a random effect from these will be selected.

    To see what the effects are like, test them!

@{b}Sphere refraction index@{ub}

    Applies to Glass-sphere.

    Sets the strength at which light is `bent' in the glass sphere. A value
    of 1000 lets light straight through without bending it. A value near
    1900 bends nearly all light to one point, which causes one pixel to be
    extremely magnified. A value over 1900 will cross the light inside the
    sphere, inverting the area below it. Experiment to find out what value
    you like the most, 1500 is the default setting.

    Example refraction indexes:

        @{b}o@{ub} 1333 is water.
        @{b}o@{ub} 1613 is silicon-glass.
        @{b}o@{ub} 1510 is crown-glass.
        @{b}o@{ub} 1362 is Ethanol (You might like this one. ;) ).
        @{b}o@{ub} 2417 is Diamond.

    @{i}NOTE: @{ui}The range is actually between 1.000 and 5.000, but the
    adjustment goes between 1000 and 5000, since GarshneBlanker only
    supports integers in sliders.

    The refraction indexes are for Yellow (589,3 nm) light, emitted by
    Sodium (Na), traveling through 20°C air at 1,013 bar pressure.

@{b}Twirl angle@{ub}

    The angle which the center-point has turned relative to the outer edge.
    Higher values twist more.

@{b}Ripple-, Twirple-, and G-Ripple amount@{ub}

    Sets the amount of `waves' for Ripples, Twirples, and Glass Ripples
    respectively.

@{b}Twirple strength@{ub}

    Sets the twirl strength of the Twirple-waves.

@{b}G-Ripple refr. index@{ub}

    Works as Sphere refraction index, but applies to Glass Ripples.

@{b}Black Hole pull@{ub}

    Sets the force at which graphics are pulled towards the center of the
    Black Hole.

@{b}Flower power@{ub}

    Sets the pull-strength of the flower-leaves.

@{b}Flower leaves@{ub}

    Sets the amount of leaves for a flower. Generally, an odd number of
    leaves looks better.

@endnode
